1. ## Overview

Project / Feature Name: Mindmap Web Software

Summary: This specification outlines the functional requirements and technical details for a Mind Map web software. This web software allows users to organize their thoughts in a graphical manner, with nodes representing ideas or notes and subnodes for organization. This software is not intended for any specific usage, but should be adaptable and usable for a variety of purposes, including: note taking, project planning, idea mapping, etc. This spec is only scoped to a webâ€“native prototype in [Next.js](http://Next.js), which uses localStorage to persist data.

Goals: Allow users to organize thoughts and ideas in a graphic manner and persist to localStorage. Display these thoughts and ideas in a visually appealing, easy to navigate interface that lacks clutter and is simple.  
Non-Goals: Enforce one usage of the mind map, rather being open ended and easy enough to use for any purpose.

2. ## Requirements

Functional Requirements:

* Users can:  
  * Edit one mind map that is represented, both visually and in data, as a tree with one parent node at level 0  
  * Add subnodes to any node, which they can add a title to and next  
  * Traverse up and down the tree both by clicking the nodes and using keyboard shortcuts  
  * Edit existing nodes  
  * Delete any node except the level 0 parent node, though this deletion will cascade and delete all subnodes. Give a confirmation message  
* Users will see:  
  * At any time, see the current node they are viewing  
  * See the subnodes as small connected nodes to the large node, with their titles but not all their text  
  * If the current node is clicked, a panel will pop up on the side with the actual contents, option to edit, etc  
  * A back button to go up to the parent node (unless current node \= node 0\)

		

3. ## Data Model

Store data in local storage, represented as a nested JSON. each node will have the following data interface:

* id: number  
* level: number  
* title: string  
* contents: string  
* children: node\[\]
